1. # Async Programming Rules
2. 
3. Blazor's sync context guarantees single-threaded component execution. All rules below follow from this.
4. 
5. ## Await every Task
6. 
7. `await` every `Task` by default — discarded tasks silently lose exceptions. The only exception: fire-and-forget where the called method wraps its body in `try/catch` and routes errors via `DispatchExceptionAsync` (see Fire-and-Forget section below).
8. 
9. ```csharp
10. // DO
11. private async Task LoadData()
12. {
13.     items = await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items");
14. }
15. 
16. // DON'T — fire-and-forget hides exceptions
17. private void LoadData()
18. {
19.     _ = Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items");
20. }
21. ```
22. 
23. ## Forbidden Primitives
24. 
25. These deadlock or escape the sync context. Never use in components:
26. 
27. | Forbidden | Why |
28. |-----------|-----|
29. | `Thread.Start` / `new Thread` | Escapes sync context |
30. | `Task.Run` | Offloads to thread-pool; `StateHasChanged` throws |
31. | `.Result` / `.Wait()` | Deadlocks sync context |
32. | `Task.ContinueWith` | Continuation runs outside sync context |
33. | `Channel<T>`, `BlockingCollection<T>`, concurrent collections | Unnecessary — single-threaded access guaranteed |
34. 
35. ```csharp
36. // DON'T — Task.Run escapes sync context
37. _ = Task.Run(async () => {
38.     var result = await OrderService.SubmitAsync(order);
39.     StateHasChanged(); // InvalidOperationException!
40. });
41. 
42. // DO — stay on sync context
43. private async Task ProcessOrder()
44. {
45.     var result = await OrderService.SubmitAsync(order);
46.     message = result.Message;
47. }
48. ```
49. 
50. ## StateHasChanged
51. 
52. Framework auto-renders after lifecycle methods and event handlers complete. Don't call `StateHasChanged` routinely.
53. 
54. **Call only for:**
55. 
56. 1. **Intermediate updates** between multiple awaits:
57. ```csharp
58. private async Task ProcessSteps()
59. {
60.     status = "Step 1...";
61.     await Step1Async();
62.     status = "Step 2...";
63.     StateHasChanged(); // intermediate update
64.     await Step2Async();
65. }
66. ```
67. 
68. 2. **External events** (timer, C# event, WebSocket) via `InvokeAsync`:
69. ```csharp
70. private async void OnExternalEvent(object? sender, EventArgs e)
71. {
72.     try
73.     {
74.         await InvokeAsync(() => { count++; StateHasChanged(); });
75.     }
76.     catch (Exception ex)
77.     {
78.         await DispatchExceptionAsync(ex);
79.     }
80. }
81. ```
82. 
83. `InvokeAsync` marshals onto the sync context. `StateHasChanged` from a raw thread throws `InvalidOperationException`. Use `async void` for external event handlers — it's the only place `async void` is appropriate in Blazor. Always `await InvokeAsync` and route errors via `DispatchExceptionAsync`.
84. 
85. ## Fire-and-Forget
86. 
87. Route errors via `DispatchExceptionAsync` (activates error boundaries, logs like lifecycle exceptions):
88. 
89. ```csharp
90. private void SendReport() => _ = SendReportCore();
91. 
92. private async Task SendReportCore()
93. {
94.     try { await ReportSender.SendAsync(); }
95.     catch (Exception ex) { await DispatchExceptionAsync(ex); }
96. }
97. ```
98. 
99. ## Alternatives to Forbidden Primitives
100. 
101. **Instead of `Task.Run`** — use `await` directly or `Task.Yield`:
102. 
103. ```csharp
104. // Yield to let renderer paint, then continue on sync context
105. private async Task StartLongOperation()
106. {
107.     status = "Starting...";
108.     await Task.Yield();
109.     await LongOperationService.RunAsync();
110.     status = "Done!";
111. }
112. ```
113. 
114. **Chunked CPU work** — break with `Task.Yield` so UI stays responsive:
115. 
116. ```csharp
117. private async Task ProcessLargeList()
118. {
119.     for (var i = 0; i < items.Count; i++)
120.     {
121.         ProcessItem(items[i]);
122.         if (i % 100 == 0)
123.         {
124.             StateHasChanged();
125.             await Task.Yield();
126.         }
127.     }
128. }
129. ```
130. 
131. **Indivisible long ops** — `Task.WhenAny` + `Task.Delay` for progress:
132. 
133. ```csharp
134. private async Task RunLongQuery()
135. {
136.     var queryTask = DatabaseService.RunExpensiveQueryAsync();
137.     while (queryTask != await Task.WhenAny(queryTask, Task.Delay(1000)))
138.     {
139.         status = "Still working...";
140.         StateHasChanged();
141.     }
142.     result = await queryTask;
143. }
144. ```
145. 
146. ### Instead of `.Result` / `.Wait()` — use `await`
147. 
148. ```csharp
149. // Wrong — blocks the sync context, deadlocks the circuit
150. private void Load()
151. {
152.     var data = Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items").Result;
153. }
154. 
155. // Correct — use async all the way through
156. private async Task Load()
157. {
158.     var data = await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items");
159. }
160. ```
161. 
162. When the calling context is synchronous and cannot be changed to `async` (e.g., an interface method that returns `void`), use fire-and-forget with error handling:
163. 
164. ```csharp
165. private void Load()
166. {
167.     _ = LoadAsync();
168. }
169. 
170. private async Task LoadAsync()
171. {
172.     try
173.     {
174.         data = await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items");
175.         StateHasChanged();
176.     }
177.     catch (Exception ex)
178.     {
179.         await DispatchExceptionAsync(ex);
180.     }
181. }
182. ```
183. 
184. `StateHasChanged` is required here because the framework does not know about the fire-and-forget task, so it will not trigger a re-render when it completes.
185. 
186. ### Instead of `ConcurrentDictionary` / `Channel<T>` — use plain collections
187. 
188. Because the synchronization context guarantees single-threaded access within a circuit, regular `Dictionary<K,V>`, `List<T>`, and `Queue<T>` are safe. Concurrent collections add overhead with no benefit:
189. 
190. ```csharp
191. // Wrong — unnecessary overhead, hides the threading model
192. private readonly ConcurrentDictionary<string, int> cache = new();
193. 
194. // Correct — the sync context already prevents concurrent access
195. private readonly Dictionary<string, int> cache = [];
196. ```
197. 
198. ### Instead of `Task.ContinueWith` — use `await` with code after it
199. 
200. ```csharp
201. // Wrong — continuation may run on a thread-pool thread
202. private void Start()
203. {
204.     _ = Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items")
205.         .ContinueWith(t =>
206.         {
207.             items = t.Result;
208.             StateHasChanged(); // InvalidOperationException!
209.         });
210. }
211. 
212. // Correct — straightforward async/await
213. private async Task Start()
214. {
215.     items = await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>("api/items");
216. }
217. ```
218. 
219. ## Cancelling async work with CancellationToken
220. 
221. Components that start long-running async operations (HTTP calls, database queries, streaming) should cancel that work when the component is disposed — typically when the user navigates away.
222. 
223. Use a `CancellationTokenSource` that is cancelled in `DisposeAsync`:
224. 
225. ```razor
226. @implements IAsyncDisposable
227. @inject HttpClient Http
228. 
229. <p>@status</p>
230. 
231. @code {
232.     private string status = "Loading...";
233.     private CancellationTokenSource cts = new();
234. 
235.     protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()
236.     {
237.         try
238.         {
239.             var data = await Http.GetFromJsonAsync<List<Item>>(
240.                 "api/items", cts.Token);
241.             status = $"Loaded {data?.Count} items.";
242.         }
243.         catch (OperationCanceledException)
244.         {
245.             // Component was disposed while loading — expected, nothing to do.
246.         }
247.     }
248. 
249.     public ValueTask DisposeAsync()
250.     {
251.         cts.Cancel();
252.         cts.Dispose();
253.         return ValueTask.CompletedTask;
254.     }
255. }
256. ```
257.

